how can I tell whether my currently installed version has it or not?

Gemini said
You can tell if your version supports it by checking the logs Kanata generates when it starts up.

Method 1: Check the Startup Logs
Run Kanata in your terminal with any configuration file. Look for an information line near the top of the output:

Bash
# Run your existing kanata binary
kanata --cfg your_config.kbd
If you see: [INFO] NOTE: kanata was compiled to never allow cmd

Result: You have the standard version. Commands will not work even if you try to enable them.

If you don't see that line: * Result: You likely have the cmd-allowed version.

Method 2: Test it in your Config
If you want to be 100% sure, you can try to "force" the feature on in your configuration file.

Open your .kbd file.

Add danger-enable-cmd yes inside the defcfg block:

Lisp
(defcfg
  danger-enable-cmd yes
)
Run Kanata.

If your binary does not support commands, it will immediately crash or show an error saying:

help: cmd is not enabled for this kanata executable (did you use 'cmd_allowed' variants?)

Why the extra step?
Even if you have the cmd-allowed binary, Kanata requires that danger-enable-cmd yes flag in your config file as a safety "double-check." This prevents a situation where you accidentally run a config you downloaded from the internet that contains malicious commands.

